ğŸŒŸ Day 19: GFG160 Challenge ğŸŒŸ

ğŸš€ Problem: Minimum Characters to Add for Palindrome

ğŸ’¡ Approach:
Utilized the LPS (Longest Prefix Suffix) array from the KMP algorithm:
1ï¸âƒ£ Concatenate the string with a special character $ and its reverse (s + '$' + reverse(s)).
2ï¸âƒ£ Compute the LPS array for this concatenated string.
3ï¸âƒ£ The last value in the LPS array gives the length of the longest palindromic prefix.
4ï¸âƒ£ Subtract this length from the original string length to get the minimum characters needed.

ğŸ’» Complexity:
âœ… Time: O(n), efficient traversal for LPS computation.
âœ… Space: O(n), for storing the LPS array.

ğŸ”‘ Result: Optimized method to transform a string into a palindrome! ğŸš€âœ…


// C++ program for getting minimum character to be
// added at front to make string palindrome

#include <algorithm>
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
using namespace std;

vector<int> computeLPSArray(string &pat) {
    int n = pat.length();
    vector<int> lps(n);

    // lps[0] is always 0
    lps[0] = 0;
    int len = 0;

    // loop calculates lps[i] for i = 1 to M-1
    int i = 1;
    while (i < n) {

        // If the characters match, increment len
        // and set lps[i]
        if (pat[i] == pat[len]) {
            len++;
            lps[i] = len;
            i++;
        }

        // If there is a mismatch
        else if (pat[i] != pat[len]) {

            // If len is not zero, update len to
            // the last known prefix length
            if (len != 0) {
                len = lps[len - 1];
            }

            // No prefix matches, set lps[i] to 0
            else {
                lps[i] = 0;
                i++;
            }
        }
    }
    return lps;
}

// Method returns minimum character to be added at
// front to make string palindrome
int minChar(string &s) {
    int n = s.length();
    string rev = s;
    reverse(rev.begin(), rev.end());

    // Get concatenation of string, special character
    // and reverse string
    s = s + "$" + rev;

    //  Get LPS array of this concatenated string
    vector<int> lps = computeLPSArray(s);

    // By subtracting last entry of lps vector from
    // string length, we will get our result
    return (n - lps.back());
}

int main() {
    string s = "AACECAAAA";
    cout << minChar(s);
    return 0;
}
